s since World War II.In his introduction, Joshua A. Fogel raises the significant moral and historiographical issues that frame the other essays. Mark Eykholt then provides an account of postwar Chinese responses to the massacre. Takashi Yoshida assesses the attempts to downplay the incident and its effects, providing a revealing analysis of Japanese debates over Japan's role in the world and the continuing ambivalence of many Japanese toward their defeat in World War II. In the concluding essay, Daqing Yang widens the scope of the discussion by comparing the Nanjing historiographic debates to similar debates in Germany over the nature of the Holocaust.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHistoriography. 0aJapanesexAttitudes. 0aMoral motivation. 4aHistoriography. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Historiography.2bisacsh1 aEykholt, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFogel, Joshua A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFogel, Joshua A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMaier, Charles S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaier, Charles S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aYang, Daqing, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYoshida, Takashi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022007240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092351540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520923515423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520923515/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013 